<p>

A look at the Internet in 1995, from a TV episode of a show called “Computer Chronicles” (May 2, 1995):

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://archive.org/details/CC1232_internet">http://<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>archive.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>org/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>details/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>CC<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>1232_<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>internet</A>
</blockquote>

The computers used these big boxy monitors; the Internet at the time was a combination of Usenet Newsgroups, FTP sites, and mostly-text webpages. People used only Mosaic to surf the World Wide Web in this episode.

<p>

This episode has also been uploaded, in lower resolution, to YouTube:

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XluovrUA6Bk">http://<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>www.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>youtube.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>com/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>watch?<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>v=<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Xluovr<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>UA<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>6<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>Bk</A>
</blockquote>

La Peña Cultural Center, whose webpage can be seen in this episode (No accents back then—it’s spelled La Pena in the pictures of their 1995 webpage), is still around:

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://lapena.org/">http://lapena.org/</A>
</blockquote>

Another web site seen in this episode, <A href="http://apc.org/">http://apc.org/</A>, is also still around.

<p>

